[],I noticed this Javascript error when testing the feature widget (testing with the Jira collector).  The issue seems to be that the issue's summary has a single quote `'` in the text.

This is happening in [hideEmpty.js](https://github.com/Hygieia/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/src/app/dashboard/directives/hideEmpty.js#L23).  In particular, when being called from [widgets/feature/view.js:231](https://github.com/Hygieia/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/src/components/widgets/feature/view.html#L231).  I tried removing the single quotes on that line, so that it looks like:
which seems to eliminate the error.
Update: ~Anyways, it doesn't seem to be affecting any actual behavior at the moment, but I thought I'd report this.~  See my next post - this is affecting the widget.

angular.js:14199 Error: [$parse:syntax] Syntax Error: Token 'd' is unexpected, expecting []] at column 48 of the expression [['{""sNumber"":""DD-9"",""sName"":""As a developer, I'd like to update story status during the sprint >> Click the Active sprints link at the top right of the screen to go to the Active sprints where the current Sprint's items can be updated"",""sUrl"":""https://jira.xxxxxxxx.com/browse/DD-9"",""changeDate"":""2019-07-07T17:35:46.000+0000"",""sEstimate"":"""",""sEstimateTime"":""0"",""sStatus"":""backlog""}']] starting at [d like to update story status during the sprint >> Click the Active sprints link at the top right of the screen to go to the Active sprints where the current Sprint's items can be updated"",""sUrl"":""https://jira.xxxxxxxx.com/browse/DD-9"",""changeDate"":""2019-07-07T17:35:46.000+0000"",""sEstimate"":"""",""sEstimateTime"":""0"",""sStatus"":""backlog""}']].

When the error occurs, the widget displays `No data found.`.  When I strip out the single quotes, my issues appear in the ""Issues in Progress"" section.  This could possible be the same issue seen in #3055  edtan
The `lastUpdateTime` can be a Date in mongo, so handle this case.

Cleaned up the test a bit, added ToStringBuilder (it's already on the classpath). Needed to add a ""TestAdapter/Wrapper"" so we could get access to the `getOptions()` so the field could be set with the Date value.

It definitely makes sense to normalized the status field from JIRA to something domain specific to Hygieia. However I think this logic needs to be expanded and probably configurable for each user as most of our JIRA configurations will have many values for status and the default being to go to ""Backlog"" is probably not what most users would expect.
I would like to hear what you all think about having this configured in something similar to:
# Now we need to map your status to a more generalized Open, In Progress, Done, or Backlog.
# The 'Backlog' status will just filter those results from the metrics entirely
# The 'Open' will be what is left over from those not In Progress or Done.
# These following statuses calculates as a part of WIP
# This is used to filter out the results so they are not a part of the tallied results
I've got some code started around this so I can use Hygieia for one of my projects using Kanban with many statuses. I would be happy to submit a PR, but wanted to get some input first.
Looking through the code, I was surprised to find the rest url:

does not return only what is on the active board, but what is in the entire project (even the backlog).",467799107,3047,Normalized JIRA Status,2019-07-14 06:00:12,2019-07-14 06:00:12,open,0,cgorshing,,
[],"Ive been looking for a tool to aggregate DevOps events (and, eventually, metrics) from a variety of distributed sources.
Hygieias feature set is the strongest Ive found, but from what Ive read it seems like the architecture is decidedly built on a pull model (I.e. via collectors).

Im sure there are good reasons for this, but Im wondering if Hygieia supports a push model out of the box, or if this capability has been discussed or road-mapped? If not, Id love to discuss the merits of the push approach and learn how (or if) others would recommend implementing such a hook.

[],,461360614,3007,What is the use of team widget and log widget and what does it monitor,2019-06-27 07:21:09,2019-07-02 18:17:16,open,3,mitunmbj,,506395932 @stevegal can you provide context here? Sbrenthughes

506437284 the Log widget is for the operations side of your application when it is deployed into an environment. It charts the number of times an event has happened in the logs being tracked based on the the filters provided and charts these up in each collection period. You can use it to provide a monitor dashboard within Hygieia for your application. At the moment there is only 1 collector which collects from cloudwatch, but there is nothing preventing other collectors from publishing this data.

507789793 Team widget is to display resource tracking at team level. It will display open reqs / full-time/part-time resources count for a team and enables recruitment prioritization. Collector is WIP. nireeshT

At quick glance it looks like the `properties-builder.sh` for that collector is out of date and I think that's breaking your setup. To get it running you'll need to modify `collectors/build/jenkins-codequality/docker/properties-builder.sh` so it spits out settings that match [what the documentation says the config should be.](https://hygieia.github.io/Hygieia/jira.html#sample-application-properties-file)
As an aside I believe they recommend using the Jenkins plugin if possible. I believe it collects everything that the three Jenkins collectors do and a bit more. OneMoreByte

# Collector types (not required, but regex should match only the type specified)

511858539 Okay the collector depends on the `Epic` issue type being used. If it isn't being used then the collector will not work in the current version.  Sbrenthughes

You need to add them in a comma separated string to `jiraIssueTypeNames`. Ex `feature.jiraIssueTypeNames=Stroy,Epic,Defect, etc`
`Epic` is required in the list.  Sbrenthughes

501361074 After pulling the code I think I see the issue. There is paging already on this. It calculated the total records and divides by the PAGE_SIZE and rounds up to the correct number of pages needed to pull the records. When it pulls the record it adds &p=pageNumber but from what I can tell it doesn't send the pagesize. The max page size is 500, however, when I ran this query without setting the page size it looks like the default is 100. so it only returns 100 records at a time but the for loop is assuming 500 records at a time so only 1/5 of the records are returned. My suggestion is to either pass in the pageSize in the url as well or reduce the PAGE_SIZE to 100 to use the default. irwindouglas

499676508 Different browsers have different restrictions on local host cors policy. You could add allow headers in the api, but that could open up a serious misconfiguration attack vector to the casual user. 1. If repo credentials are configured in repo config widget then it is given priority.
2. When repo credentials are missing in config widget then use globally configured credentials.
3. If no credentials are configured(repo config/globally) then make Rest API call without credentials.

492251253 > * for collectorItemOnlyUpdate, ""true"" setting failed for me because there weren't any widgets set up, so it didn't bring back any boards.  Since widget config is done using the populated list of projects and boards, it seems like it _has_ to be ""false"" so users have something to pick.

The Jira Collector doesn't work like this. Only issues are impacted by `collectorItemOnlyUpdate`. Projects and boards/teams pull by default. So you can configure the widget before it collects more data.

> I still don't see why it doesn't initially pull all stories in current sprints. The JQL I ran showed thousand of stories in open sprints across the org. I can't find a pattern as to which items are collected and which aren't. Are there any common errors in config that cause this?

Are all the stories actually of issue type `Story`? Since they didn't pull with `collectorItemOnlyUpdate=false` I suspect not. For now you need to add the issue types here `feature.jiraIssueTypeNames=` and their ids `feature.jiraStoryIds[]=`.  We will be making an enhancment soon where the need for `feature.jiraStoryIds[]` and `feature.jiraEpicId` will go away.  Sbrenthughes

and the rally settings should initialize the arrayLists to avoid NPE. fidelcoria-aa

[],Problem: When attempting to rehome to a new MongoDB, it fails to authenticate. Sniffer capture shows it is not using the `admin` DB in Mongo to authenticate, rather it is trying to auth against the DB where Hygieia will be storing its data.

[{address=REDACTED:27021, type=UNKNOWN, state=CONNECTING, exception={com.mongodb.MongoSecurityException: Exception authenticating MongoCredential{mechanism=SCRAM-SHA-1, userName='REDACTED', source='REDACTED_DB_NAME', password=<hidden>, mechanismProperties={}}}, caused by {com.mongodb.MongoCommandException: Command failed with error 18: 'Authentication failed.' on server REDACTED:27021. The full response is { ""ok"" : 0.0, ""errmsg"" : ""Authentication failed."", ""code"" : 18, ""codeName"" : ""AuthenticationFailed"",

... where `REDACTED_DB_NAME` is the name of the DB that Hygieia will store its data, should it be able to auth... which is the same DB I see in the sniffer caps it is trying to perform initial auth to, instead of `admin`.
I have connected to the same Mongo cluster with the same creds - though using the `admin` DB to auth, of course - and it works fine.
I did try changing some of the Spring Boot config relevant to this (e.g.: `spring.data.mongodb.authentication-database=admin`), but no joy.

Is there something I'm missing here, or is the code hardwired to assume that the user lives in Hygieia's DB, instead of `admin`?",440873108,2877,"Unable to get services to auth against ""admin"" DB in Mongo; uses Hygieia's DB, instead",2019-05-06 20:28:59,2019-06-04 17:43:48,open,5,cjchand,,"489764934 I should mention that I can take the same setup and point it to a single-box Mongo where I added the user per the directions (e.g.: user lives in the same DB as Hygieia's data) and that works fine. cjchand
489785690 @cjchand Can you help me understand what is your requirement? rvema

It is very common practice in Mongo to build users in the `admin` DB, not the DB where the data lives. This means when you go to authenticate to Mongo, you do so against the `admin` DB and not the DB for Hygieia.
In fact, there is a Spring property for this: [spring.data.mongodb.authentication-database](https://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/docs/1.3.0.RELEASE/reference/html/common-application-properties.html).
What I'm asking for is the ability to specify what DB to auth against. I tried setting `spring.data.mongodb.authentication-database=admin` in my application.properties, but it ignored that setting.
498497900 @cjchand Have you tried using `dbname=dashboarddb` in your properties? rvema
498772733 @rvema Yes, it works if I add my account to the Hygieia DB itself. However, this is not standard practice for many MongoDB installs.

Instead, all users - regardless of the DB(s) they use - are typically added to the `admin` DB, then granted rights to the DB(s) they need to access. In fact, [MongoDB stores all users in the admin DB regardless of what DB you create the account in](https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/core/security-users/#centralized-user-data).

So, the ask here is that there be a property to tell Hygieia services what DB to auth against. You can default it to the same DB Hygieia uses (`dashboarddb`, etc), but give users the ability to specify a different DB solely for auth, if needed. Again, there is a [Spring property for this in the MongoDB class you are using](https://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/docs/1.3.0.RELEASE/reference/html/common-application-properties.html), just to reinforce that what I'm calling out here is indeed common.

1. The error threshold in collector property file is too low. Network is never perfect IMHO. I set it to 100. https://github.com/Hygieia/Hygieia/blob/master/collectors/scm/github/docker/properties-builder.sh#L26

2. I added more info about the error by changing `repo.getRepoUrl()` to `ex.getMessage()+"" : ""+repo.getRepoUrl()` in the exception handlers in https://github.com/Hygieia/Hygieia/blob/master/collectors/scm/github/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/collector/GitHubCollectorTask.java#L237-L246 . This way, it shows up clearly in the tooltip of the red dot right in the UI.

3. To remove/reset the yellow/red dot, I ran this instruction in MongoDB (Figure your correct object identifier): `db.collector_items.update({""_id"":ObjectId(""5af2fa6936d1a0000117a972"")},{""$set"": {""errors"": []}});`

[],Recently, I started a conversation for my opensource contribution in Hygieia project and I was instructed to remove my copyright (the entity I am representing) section from the source code I wanted to contribute.
In this context, I am opening this issue in a hope that we can solidify OSS contribution process for Hygieia project.

I have explored some other popular opensource project and how they manage OSS contributions. Here I will take the example of Spring Framework and Apples Swift project and highlight their OSS contribution process.

- **Spring Framework**: Spring project enforces contributors to sign [Contributors License Agreement](https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-framework/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#code-of-conduct) Please see [Pivotal CLA](https://cla.pivotal.io/about) for more details on why this is needed.
- **Swift**: Contributing guide to swift opensource project can be found in [Swift Contribution Guide]( https://swift.org/contributing/#contributing-code)

Swift project maintainers clearly mention list of copyright headers in the [CONTRIBUTORS.txt](https://swift.org/CONTRIBUTORS.txt) file. This file include all the contributors. Please see their license details [Swift License](https://swift.org/community/#license)
These projects protect copyright and make contributors copyright easily traceable.
Looking forward to collaborating and I am happy to provide additional details on this topic(if required).

[],So, I have been asked to evaluate Hygieia for use with our stack and right away I suspect the Bitbucket cloud connector only supports API v1. I say this based on documentation that refers to the `v1/api`
As well as looking at [The actual code](https://github.com/Hygieia/Hygieia/search?q=DefaultBitbucketCloudClient&unscoped_q=DefaultBitbucketCloudClient)

The whole reason this is an issue is because [bitbucket is discontinuing the 1.0 endpoint in April](https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/bitbucket/deprecation-notice-v1-apis/) and it's significantly different than 2.0 - I know this because I just got done with a lot of integration straddling between them
Also, not directly related but important: BB is deprecating API tokens in favor of OAUTH

**My issue:** Am I correct in my assumptions about V2 support for BB?",413555534,2746,BB Connector support for BB API 2.0,2019-02-22 19:56:55,2019-06-05 17:59:53,open,2,chb0github,,"498640247 @shishirchaturvedi any thoughts here? rvema
498912542 @chb0github I think you are right. This is the code which fetches commits,

I didn't find `/repositories/` path in the rest API URL. This doesn't match with [BB Rest API v2](https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/resource/repositories/%7Busername%7D/%7Brepo_slug%7D/commits)
In Hygieia SCM collector, the main mechanism for authenticating REST API is HTTP header authentication.
I am not using Bitbucket Cloud so I can't test its integration in Hygieia.

As you are using Bitbucket Cloud so you can take current implementation for Bitbucket Cloud in Hygieia as starting point and can enhance it to support V2 and [Oauth2](https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucket/oauth-on-bitbucket-cloud-238027431.html).

**in properties-builder.sh, there is a mistake having it generate ""application.properties"" when test_script is defined or /config/hygieia-jenkins-build-collector.properties**

`substitute-nginx-proxy-pass.sh` is placed in `./nginx-start/` at build time to correctly set the API server hostname
`api.conf` is a `proxy_pass` snippet that is placed in `./nginx-default-cfg/` for proper routing to the API server

[],Have been tracking down the source of a frustrating issue where Jenkins build collector doesn't seem to respect settings from configuration.
Commented out these lines from the `properties-builder.sh` and it resolved the issue

It would seem this would allow for the properties file to be created in the wrong location. Where the config would be written to `config/hygieia-jenkins-build-collector.properties` but the application will be started with

Where `$PROP_FILE` is provided by the Dockerfile as `ENV PROP_FILE /hygieia/config/application.properties`",401551778,2681,Inconsistencies in docker property-builder script causing unexpected failure due to misconfiguration,2019-01-22 00:23:27,2019-01-25 18:43:49,open,5,spyoungtech,,"456233165 Also noteworthy is that this ""local testing"" block doesn't appear in all the collectors' `properties-builder.sh`.

Similar code is found in scripts for xldeploy, appdynamics, and gitlab. I don't use those collectors, but presumably, this problem would exist for those using these collectors with docker-compose. spyoungtech
456245114 Please see MatthewBeasleys comment here: https://github.com/Hygieia/Hygieia/issues/2489. It describes how to override the properties file.

But we do need to update the documentation and make it consistent across the collectors. Also, there will be an over haul of the docker setup contributed back to the project soon. So stay tuned.  Sbrenthughes
456246755 Thanks for that link @Sbrenthughes . Looking forward to changes in the docker setup.

I have a couple reservations about overriding the environment variable, particularly because the `PROP_FILE` variable in the shell script can change based on the presence of this `TEST_SCRIPT` environment variable, and will change regardless of what value is supplied in the environment variable.

In other words, I believe these lines in `properties-builder.sh` to be harmful. Yes, one can override the dockerfile default location to accommodate, but that is treating the symptom rather than root cause.

The Dockerfile cmd will always start the app with the location in environment variable; behaves as expected. The properties-builder script will not respect the environment variable, which is the root cause of this issue.

I would suggest that the environment variable be respected in all cases and that instead of using those lines in the shell script... A tester should override the environment variable instead of using a separate variable `TEST_SCRIPT`.

Also weird that I'd need to do this environment variable override for just these few collectors, which is why it seems (in my view) like a bug that should be fixed, rather than documenting a workaround. spyoungtech
Agree with @spyoungtech . Which is why I never did the PR for documentation - I felt that it should be fixed rather than workaround documented.
Glad to see it will be addressed in the Docker setup overhaul.  daniel-ng
